# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: impeller
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The **1 euro cent coin** (€0.01) has a value of one hundredth of a euro and is composed of copper-covered steel.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] It is the lowest-value coin in the Eurozone; the next lowest are the 2 and 5 euro cent coins.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] All euro coins have a common reverse and a country-specific (national) obverse.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The coin has been used since 2002 and was not redesigned in 2007 as was the case with the higher-value coins.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The coin dates from 2002, when euro coins and banknotes were introduced in the then 12-member eurozone and its related territories.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Despite this, the coins of some countries were issued beginning in 1999.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The common side was designed by Luc Luycx, a Belgian artist who won a Europe-wide competition to design the new coins.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The design of the 1- to 5-cent coins was intended to show the European Union's (EU) place in the world (relative to Africa and Asia), as opposed to the one- and two-euro coins showing the 15 states as one and the 10- to 50-cent coins showing separate EU states.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The national sides, then 15 (eurozone + Monaco, San Marino and the Vatican, who could mint their own), were each designed according to national competitions, though to specifications which applied to all coins, such as the requirement of including twelve stars (see euro coins for more).
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] National designs were not allowed to change until the end of 2008, unless a monarch (whose portrait usually appears on the coins) dies or abdicates.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] This happened in Monaco and the Vatican City, resulting in three new designs in circulation (the Vatican had an interim *sede vacante* design until the new Pope was elected).
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] However, starting in 2007, some national designs underwent minor changes due to regulations requiring national designs to meet a series of specifications.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] As the EU's membership has since expanded in 2004 and 2007, with further expansions envisaged, the common face of all euro coins from the value of 10 cent and above were redesigned in 2007 to show a new map.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The 1- to 5-cent coins, however, did not change, as the highlighting of the old members over the globe was so faint it was not considered worth the cost.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] However, new national coin designs were added in 2007 with the entry in the eurozone of Slovenia, in 2008 with Cyprus and Malta, in 2009 with Slovakia, in 2011 with Estonia, in 2014 with Latvia, in 2015 with Lithuania, in 2023 with Croatia, and in 2026 with Bulgaria.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Andorra began minting its own designs in 2014 after winning the right to do so.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The coins are composed of copper-covered steel, with a diameter of 16.25 mm, a 1.67 mm thickness and a mass of 2.30 grams.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The coins have been used from 2002, though some are dated 1999 which is the year the euro was created as a currency, but not put into general circulation.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The reverse was designed by Luc Luycx and displays a globe in the bottom right.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The then-fifteen members of the EU are lightly highlighted and the northern half of Africa and the western half of Asia (including the Middle East) are shown.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Six fine lines cut diagonally behind the globe from each side of the coin and have twelve stars at their ends (reflective of the flag of Europe).
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] To the top left is a large number 1 followed, in smaller text, by the words "EURO CENT".
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The designer's initials, LL, appear to the right of the globe.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Starting in 2017 coins from individual member states have started adjusting their common side design to a new version, identified by smaller and more rounded numeral "1" and longer lines outside of the stars at the coin's circumference.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The obverse side of the coin depends on the issuing country.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] All have to include the name or an abbreviation of the issuing country.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The national side of circulation coins shall bear a circle of 12 stars that shall fully surround the national design, including the year mark and the indication of the issuing Member State’s name.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The side cannot repeat the denomination of the coin unless the issuing country uses an alphabet other than Latin.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Currently, Greece, Cyprus and Bulgaria are the only such countries.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Greece engraves "1 ΛΕΠΤΟ" (1 lepto) on its coins and Bulgaria engraves "СТОТИНКА" (stotinka).
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Austria ignores this rule, engraving "EIN EURO CENT" on its coins, hence will have to change its design to comply this rule.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Belgium, Finland, France, the Netherlands and Spain minted coins dated 1999, 2000 and 2001 although these entered circulation in 2002.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Monaco minted coins dated 2001 although these entered circulation in 2002 too.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Austria, Germany and Greece will also at some point need to update their designs to comply with guidelines stating they must include the issuing state's name or initial, and not repeat the denomination of the coin (Austria only).
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] On the other hand, Slovenia and Greece have to comply with the star rule.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] In addition, there are several EU states that have not yet adopted the euro, some of them have already agreed upon their coin designs; however, it is not known exactly when they will adopt the currency, and hence these are not yet minted.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] See enlargement of the eurozone for expected entry dates of these countries.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Percentage of people in favor of abolishing the use of the 1- and 2-euro cent coins.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The one- and two-cent coins were initially introduced to ensure that the transition to the euro was not used as an excuse by retailers to heavily round up prices.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] However, each euro country will always have to accept the small coins as legal tender.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] The Nederlandsche Bank calculated it would save $36 million a year by not using the smaller coins.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] Other countries such as Germany favoured retaining the coins due to retailers' desire for €1.99 prices, which appear more attractive to the consumer than €2.00 (psychological pricing).
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] According to a 2021 Eurobarometer survey of citizens across the Eurozone, 67% of respondents were in favor of the removal of the 1 and 2 cent coins and rounding of prices; with over 75% in Finland, Ireland, Italy and Slovakia.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] All countries in the eurozone showed a plurality of people in favor of the abolishment.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] In Flemish, the 1- to 5-cent coins have the nickname *koper* (copper), *ros* (redhead) or *rostjes* (little redhead) due to their colour.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] In Portugal, the 1-cent coin gained the nicknames *botão* (button), *feijão* (bean) and *moedas-pretas* (black-coins) due to its small size, colour and value: instead of gambling with real money, buttons sometimes are used.
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] In Italy 1, 2 and 5 cent coins are called "ramini" or "bronzini", meaning respectively "little coppers" and "little bronzes".
[src:impeller/1-euro-cent-coin] In Ireland they are also known as "coppers".
[src:impeller/agitator-device] An **agitator** is a device or mechanism to put something into motion by shaking or stirring.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] There are several types of agitation machines, including washing machine agitators (which rotate back and forth) and magnetic agitators (which contain a magnetic bar rotating in a magnetic field).
[src:impeller/agitator-device] Agitators can come in many sizes and varieties, depending on the application.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] In general, agitators usually consist of an impeller and a shaft.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] An impeller is a rotor located within a tube or conduit attached to the shaft.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] It helps enhance the pressure in order for the flow of a fluid be done.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] Modern industrial agitators incorporate process control to maintain better control over the mixing process.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] In a top load washing machine the agitator projects from the bottom of the wash basket and creates the wash action by rotating back and forth, rolling garments from the top of the load, down to the bottom, then back up again.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] There are several types of agitators with the most common being the "straight-vane" and "dual-action" agitators.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] The "straight-vane" is a one-part agitator with bottom and side fins that usually turns back and forth.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] The Dual-action is a two-part agitator that has bottom washer fins that move back and forth and a spiral top that rotates clockwise to help guide the clothes to the bottom washer fins.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] The modern agitator, which is dual-action, was first made in Kenmore Appliances washing machines in the 1980s to present.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] These agitators are known by the company as dual-rollover and triple-rollover action agitators.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] This is a device formed by a metallic bar (called the agitation bar) which is normally covered by a plastic layer, and a sheet that has underneath it a rotatory magnet or a series of electromagnets arranged in a circular form to create a magnetic rotatory field.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] Commonly, the sheet has an arrangement of electric resistances that can heat some chemical solutions.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] During the operation of a typical magnetic agitator, the agitator bar is moved inside a container such as to dissolve a substance in a liquid.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] The container must be placed on the sheet, so that the magnetic field influences the agitation bar and makes it rotate.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] This allows it to mix different substances at high speeds.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] An agitation rack is a special form of agitator used to store platelets.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] It is composed of a series of clasps attached to motorised bars, that rock the specimens of platelets gently back-and-forth.
[src:impeller/agitator-device] This prevents them from becoming activated and adhering to one another, which cannot be reversed by any current means.
[src:impeller/army] An **army**, **ground force** or **land force** is an armed force that fights primarily on land.
[src:impeller/army] In the broadest sense, it is the land-based military branch, service branch, or armed service of a nation or country.
[src:impeller/army] It may also include aviation assets by possessing an army aviation component.
[src:impeller/army] Within a national military force, the word army may also mean a field army.
[src:impeller/army] In some countries, such as France and China, the term "army", especially in its plural form "armies", has the broader meaning of armed forces as a whole, while retaining the colloquial sense of land forces.
[src:impeller/army] To differentiate the colloquial army from the formal concept of military force, the term is qualified, for example, in France, the land force is called *Armée de terre*, meaning **Land Army**, and the air and space force is called *Armée de l'Air et de l’Espace*, meaning **Air and Space Army**.
[src:impeller/army] The naval force, although not using the term "army", is also included in the broad sense of the term "armies" — thus the French Navy is an integral component of the collective French Armies (French Armed Forces) under the Ministry of the Armies.
[src:impeller/army] A similar pattern is seen in China, with the People's Liberation Army (PLA) being the overall military, the land force being the PLA Ground Force, and so forth for the PLA Air Force, the PLA Navy, and other branches.
[src:impeller/army] Though by convention, irregular military is understood in contrast to regular armies, which grew slowly from personal bodyguards or elite militia.
[src:impeller/army] Regular, in this case, refers to standardized doctrines, uniforms, organizations, etc.
[src:impeller/army] Regular military can also refer to full-time status (standing army), versus reserve or part-time personnel.
[src:impeller/army] Other distinctions may separate statutory forces (established under laws such as the National Defence Act) from de facto "non-statutory" forces such as some guerrilla and revolutionary armies.
[src:impeller/army] Armies are always divided into various specialties, according to the mission, role, and training of individual units, and sometimes individual soldiers within a unit.
[src:impeller/army] During the Iron Age, the Maurya and Nanda Empires had one of the largest armies in the world, the peak being approximately over 600,000 Infantry, 30,000 Cavalry, 8,000 War-Chariots and 9,000 War Elephants not including tributary state allies.
[src:impeller/army] In the Gupta age, large armies of longbowmen were recruited to fight off invading horse archer armies.
[src:impeller/army] Elephants, pikemen, and cavalry were other featured troops.
[src:impeller/army] The states of China raised armies for at least 1000 years before the Spring and Autumn Annals.
[src:impeller/army] By the Warring States period, the crossbow had been perfected enough to become a military secret, with bronze bolts that could pierce any armor.
[src:impeller/army] Thus, any political power of a state rested on the army and its organization.
[src:impeller/army] China underwent political consolidation of the states of Han (韓), Wei (魏), Chu (楚), Yan (燕), Zhao (趙) and Qi (齊), until by 221 BCE, Qin Shi Huang (秦始皇帝), the first emperor of the Qin dynasty, attained absolute power.
[src:impeller/army] The first emperor of China could command the creation of a Terracotta Army to guard his tomb in the city of Xi'an (西安).
[src:impeller/army] In addition to a realignment of the Great Wall of China to strengthen his empire against insurrection, invasion, and incursion.
[src:impeller/army] Sun Tzu's *The Art of War* remains one of China's Seven Military Classics, even though it is two thousand years old.
[src:impeller/army] Since no political figure could exist without an army, measures were taken to ensure only the most capable leaders could control the armies.
[src:impeller/army] Civil bureaucracies (士大夫) arose to control the productive power of the states, and their military power.
[src:impeller/army] The Spartan Army was one of the earliest known professional armies.
[src:impeller/army] Boys were sent to a barracks at the age of seven or eight to train for becoming a soldier.
[src:impeller/army] At the age of thirty, they were released from the barracks and allowed to marry and have a family.
[src:impeller/army] After that, men devoted their lives to war until their retirement at the age of 60.
[src:impeller/army] The Spartan Army was largely composed of hoplites, equipped with arms and armor nearly identical to each other.
[src:impeller/army] Each hoplite bore the Spartan emblem and a scarlet uniform.
[src:impeller/army] The main pieces of this armor were a round shield, a spear and a helmet.
[src:impeller/army] The Roman Army had its origins in the citizen army of the Republic, which was staffed by citizens serving mandatory duty for Rome.
[src:impeller/army] Conscription remained the main method through which Rome mustered forces until the end of the Republic.
[src:impeller/army] The army eventually became a professional organization largely of citizens, who would served continuously for 25 years before being discharged.
[src:impeller/army] The Romans were also noted for making use of auxiliary troops, non-Romans who served with the legions and filled roles that the traditional Roman military could not fill effectively, such as light skirmish troops and heavy cavalry.
[src:impeller/army] After their service in the army they were made citizens of Rome and then their children were citizens also.
[src:impeller/army] They were also given land and money to settle in Rome.
[src:impeller/army] In the Late Roman Empire, these auxiliary troops, along with foreign mercenaries, became the core of the Roman Army; moreover, by the time of the Late Roman Empire tribes such as the Visigoths were paid to serve as mercenaries.
[src:impeller/army] In the earliest Middle Ages it was the obligation of every aristocrat to respond to the call to battle with his own equipment, archers, and infantry.
[src:impeller/army] This decentralized system was necessary due to the social order of the time, but could lead to motley forces with variable training, equipment and abilities.
[src:impeller/army] The more resources the noble had access to, the better his troops would be.
[src:impeller/army] Initially, the words "knight" and "noble" were used interchangeably as there was not generally a distinction between them.
[src:impeller/army] While the nobility did fight upon horseback, they were also supported by lower class citizens – and mercenaries and criminals – whose only purpose was participating in warfare because, most often than not, they held brief employment during their lord's engagement.
[src:impeller/army] As the Middle Ages progressed and feudalism developed in a legitimate social and economic system, knights started to develop into their own class with a minor caveat: they were still in debt to their lord.
[src:impeller/army] No longer primarily driven by economic need, the newly established vassal class were, instead, driven by fealty and chivalry.
[src:impeller/army] As central governments grew in power, a return to the citizen armies of the classical period also began, as central levies of the peasantry began to be the central recruiting tool.
[src:impeller/army] England was one of the most centralized states in the Middle Ages, and the armies that fought in the Hundred Years' War were, predominantly, composed of paid professionals.
[src:impeller/army] In theory, every Englishman had an obligation to serve for 40 days.
[src:impeller/army] Forty days was not long enough for a campaign, especially one on the continent.
[src:impeller/army] Thus the scutage was introduced, whereby most Englishmen paid to escape their service and this money was used to create a permanent army.
[src:impeller/army] However, almost all high medieval armies in Europe were composed of a great deal of paid core troops, and there was a large mercenary market in Europe from at least the early 12th century.
[src:impeller/army] As the Middle Ages progressed in Italy, Italian cities began to rely mostly on mercenaries to do their fighting rather than the militias that had dominated the early and high medieval period in this region.
[src:impeller/army] These would be groups of career soldiers who would be paid a set rate.
[src:impeller/army] Mercenaries tended to be effective soldiers, especially in combination with standing forces, but in Italy they came to dominate the armies of the city states.
[src:impeller/army] This made them considerably less reliable than a standing army.
[src:impeller/army] Mercenary-on-mercenary warfare in Italy also led to relatively bloodless campaigns which relied as much on maneuver as on battles.
[src:impeller/army] In 1439 the French legislature, known as the Estates General (French: *états généraux*), passed laws that restricted military recruitment and training to the king alone.
[src:impeller/army] There was a new tax to be raised known as the *taille* that was to provide funding for a new Royal army.
[src:impeller/army] The mercenary companies were given a choice of either joining the Royal army as *compagnies d'ordonnance* on a permanent basis, or being hunted down and destroyed if they refused.
[src:impeller/army] France gained a total standing army of around 6,000 men, which was sent out to gradually eliminate the remaining mercenaries who insisted on operating on their own.
[src:impeller/army] The new standing army had a more disciplined and professional approach to warfare than its predecessors.
[src:impeller/army] The reforms of the 1440s, eventually led to the French victory at Castillon in 1453, and the conclusion of the Hundred Years' War.
[src:impeller/army] By 1450 the companies were divided into the field army, known as the *grande ordonnance* and the garrison force known as the *petite ordonnance*.
[src:impeller/army] First nation states lacked the funds needed to maintain standing forces, so they tended to hire mercenaries to serve in their armies during wartime.
[src:impeller/army] Such mercenaries typically formed at the ends of periods of conflict, when men-at-arms were no longer needed by their respective governments.
[src:impeller/army] The veteran soldiers thus looked for other forms of employment, often becoming mercenaries.
[src:impeller/army] Free Companies would often specialize in forms of combat that required longer periods of training that was not available in the form of a mobilized militia.
[src:impeller/army] As late as the 1650s, most troops were mercenaries.
[src:impeller/army] However, after the 17th century, most states invested in better disciplined and more politically reliable permanent troops.
[src:impeller/army] For a time mercenaries became important as trainers and administrators, but soon these tasks were also taken by the state.
[src:impeller/army] The massive size of these armies required a large supporting force of administrators.
[src:impeller/army] The newly centralized states were forced to set up vast organized bureaucracies to manage these armies, which some historians argue is the basis of the modern bureaucratic state.
[src:impeller/army] The combination of increased taxes and increased centralization of government functions caused a series of revolts across Europe such as the Fronde in France and the English Civil War.
[src:impeller/army] In many countries, the resolution of this conflict was the rise of absolute monarchy.
[src:impeller/army] Only in England and the Netherlands did representative government evolve as an alternative.
[src:impeller/army] From the late 17th century, states learned how to finance wars through long term low interest loans from national banking institutions.
[src:impeller/army] The first state to master this process was the Dutch Republic.
[src:impeller/army] This transformation in the armies of Europe had great social impact.
[src:impeller/army] The defense of the state now rested on the commoners, not on the aristocrats.
[src:impeller/army] However, aristocrats continued to monopolize the officer corps of almost all early modern armies, including their high command.
[src:impeller/army] Moreover, popular revolts almost always failed unless they had the support and patronage of the noble or gentry classes.
[src:impeller/army] The new armies, because of their vast expense, were also dependent on taxation and the commercial classes who also began to demand a greater role in society.
[src:impeller/army] The great commercial powers of the Dutch and English matched much larger states in military might.
[src:impeller/army] As any man could be quickly trained in the use of a musket, it became far easier to form massive armies.
[src:impeller/army] The inaccuracy of the weapons necessitated large groups of massed soldiers.
[src:impeller/army] This led to a rapid swelling of the size of armies.
[src:impeller/army] For the first time huge masses of the population could enter combat, rather than just the highly skilled professionals.
[src:impeller/army] It has been argued that the drawing of men from across the nation into an organized corps helped breed national unity and patriotism, and during this period the modern notion of the nation state was born.
[src:impeller/army] However, this would only become apparent after the French Revolutionary Wars.
[src:impeller/army] At this time, the *levée en masse* and conscription would become the defining paradigm of modern warfare.
[src:impeller/army] Before then, however, most national armies were in fact composed of many nationalities.
[src:impeller/army] In Spain armies were recruited from all the Spanish European territories including Spain, Italy, Wallonia (Walloon Guards) and Germany.
[src:impeller/army] The French recruited some soldiers from Germany, Switzerland as well as from Piedmont.
[src:impeller/army] Britain recruited Hessian and Hanovrian troops until the late 18th century.
[src:impeller/army] Irish Catholics made careers for themselves in the armies of many Catholic European states.
[src:impeller/army] Troops for foreign expeditions were raised upon an *ad hoc* basis.
[src:impeller/army] Noblemen and professional regular soldiers were commissioned by the monarch to supply troops, raising their quotas by indenture from a variety of sources.
[src:impeller/army] On January 26, 1661 Charles II issued the Royal Warrant that created the genesis of what would become the British Army, although the Scots Army and English Army would remain two separate organizations until the unification of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:impeller/army] The small force was represented by only a few regiments.
[src:impeller/army] After the American Revolutionary War the Continental Army was quickly disbanded as part of the Americans' distrust of standing armies, and irregular state militias became the sole ground army of the United States, with the exception of one battery of artillery guarding West Point's arsenal.
[src:impeller/army] Then First American Regiment was established in 1784.
[src:impeller/army] However, because of continuing conflict with Native Americans, it was soon realized that it was necessary to field a trained standing army.
[src:impeller/army] The first of these, the Legion of the United States, was established in 1791.
[src:impeller/army] Until 1733 the common soldiers of Prussian Army consisted largely of peasantry recruited or impressed from Brandenburg–Prussia, leading many to flee to neighboring countries.
[src:impeller/army] To halt this trend, Frederick William I divided Prussia into regimental cantons.
[src:impeller/army] Every youth was required to serve as a soldier in these recruitment districts for three months each year; this met agrarian needs and added extra troops to bolster the regular ranks.
[src:impeller/army] Russian tsars before Peter I of Russia maintained professional hereditary musketeer corps (streltsy in Russian) that were highly unreliable and undisciplined.
[src:impeller/army] In times of war the armed forces were augmented by peasants.
[src:impeller/army] Peter I introduced a modern regular army built on German model, but with a new aspect: officers not necessarily from nobility, as talented commoners were given promotions that eventually included a noble title at the attainment of an officer's rank.
[src:impeller/army] Conscription of peasants and townspeople was based on quota system, per settlement.
[src:impeller/army] Initially it was based on the number of households, later it was based on the population numbers.
[src:impeller/army] The term of service in the 18th century was for life.
[src:impeller/army] In 1834 it was reduced to 20 years plus 5 years in reserve and in 1855 to 12 years plus 3 years of reserve.
[src:impeller/army] The first Ottoman standing army were Janissaries.
[src:impeller/army] They replaced forces that mostly comprised tribal warriors (*ghazis*) whose loyalty and morale could not always be trusted.
[src:impeller/army] The first Janissary units were formed from prisoners of war and slaves, probably as a result of the sultan taking his traditional one-fifth share of his army's treasure they looted in kind rather than cash.
[src:impeller/army] From the 1380s onwards, their ranks were filled under the *devşirme* system, where feudal dues were paid by service to the sultan.
[src:impeller/army] The "recruits" were mostly Christian youths, reminiscent of mamluks.
[src:impeller/army] China organized the Manchu people into the Eight Banner system in the early 17th century.
[src:impeller/army] Defected Ming armies formed the Green Standard Army.
[src:impeller/army] These troops enlisted voluntarily and for long terms of service.
[src:impeller/army] Conscription allowed the French Republic to form the *Grande Armée*, what Napoleon Bonaparte called "the nation in arms", which successfully battled European professional armies.
[src:impeller/army] Conscription, particularly when the conscripts are being sent to foreign wars that do not directly affect the security of the nation, has historically been highly politically contentious in democracies.
[src:impeller/army] In developed nations, the increasing emphasis on technological firepower and better-trained fighting forces, make mass conscription unlikely in the foreseeable future.
[src:impeller/army] Russia, as well as many other nations, retains mainly a conscript army.
[src:impeller/army] There is also a very rare *citizen army* as used in Switzerland (see Military of Switzerland).
[src:impeller/army] A particular army can be named or numbered to distinguish it from military land forces in general.
[src:impeller/army] For example, the First United States Army and the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:impeller/army] In the British Army it is normal to spell out the ordinal number of an army (e.g.
[src:impeller/army] First Army), whereas lower formations use figures (e.g.
[src:impeller/army] Armies (as well as army groups and theaters) are large formations which vary significantly between armed forces in size, composition, and scope of responsibility.
[src:impeller/army] In the Soviet Red Army and the Soviet Air Force, "Armies" could vary in size, but were subordinate to an Army Group-sized "front" in wartime.
[src:impeller/army] In peacetime, a Soviet army was usually subordinate to a military district.
[src:impeller/army] Viktor Suvorov's *Inside the Soviet Army* describes how Cold War era Soviet military districts were actually composed of a front headquarters and a military district headquarters co-located for administration and deception ('maskirovika') reasons.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] An **axial fan** is a type of fan that causes gas to flow through it in an axial direction, parallel to the shaft about which the blades rotate.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The fan is designed to produce a pressure difference, and hence force, to cause a flow through the fan.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Factors which determine the performance of the fan include the number and shape of the blades.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Fans have many applications including in wind tunnels and cooling towers.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Design parameters include power, flow rate, pressure rise and efficiency.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Axial fans generally comprise fewer blades (two to six) than centrifugal fans.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Axial fans commonly have larger radius and lower speed (ω) than ducted fans (esp. at similar power.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Since the calculation cannot be done using the inlet and outlet velocity triangles, which is not the case in other turbomachines, calculation is done by considering a mean velocity triangle for flow only through an infinitesimal blade element.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The blade is divided into many small elements and various parameters are determined separately for each element.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] In the figure, the thickness of the propeller disc is assumed to be negligible.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The boundary between the fluid in motion and fluid at rest is shown.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] In the figure, across the propeller disc, velocities (C1 and C2) cannot change abruptly across the propeller disc as that will create a shockwave but the fan creates the pressure difference across the propeller disc.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Hence the flow can be modeled where the air flows through an imaginary diverging duct, where diameter of propeller disc and diameter of the outlet are related.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] In this theory, a small element (*dr*) is taken at a distance *r* from the root of the blade and all the forces acting on the element are analysed to get a solution.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] It is assumed that the flow through each section of small radial thickness *dr* is assumed to be independent of the flow through other elements.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] No. of Blades (z) and Spacing (s) are related as, $s={\frac {2\pi r}{z}}$ and the total thrust for the elemental section of the propeller is **zΔFx**.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Finally, thrust and torque can be found out for an elemental section as they are proportional to Fx and Fy respectively.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The relationship between the pressure variation and the volume flow rate are important characteristics of fans.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The typical characteristics of axial fans can be studied from the performance curves.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The performance curve for the axial fan is shown in the figure.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The power output of the fans increases with almost constant positive slope.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The pressure fluctuations are observed at low discharges and at flow rates(as indicated by the point "S" ) the pressure deceases.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The pressure variations to the left of the point "S" causes for unsteady flow which are due to the two effects of Stalling and surging.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Stalling and surging affects the fan performance, blades, as well as output and are thus undesirable.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] They occur because of the improper design, fan physical properties and are generally accompanied by noise generation.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The cause for this is the separation of the flow from the blade surfaces.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] This effect can be explained by the flow over an air foil.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] When the angle of incidence increases (during the low velocity flow) at the entrance of the air foil, flow pattern changes and separation occurs.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] This is the first stage of stalling and through this separation point the flow separates leading to the formation of vortices, back flow in the separated region.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] For a further the explanation of stall and rotating stall, refer to compressor surge.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The stall zone for the single axial fan and axial fans operated in parallel are shown in the figure.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Many Axial fan failures have happened after controlled blade axial fans were locked in a fixed position and Variable Frequency Drives (VFDs) were installed.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The VFDs are not practical for some Axial fans.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Axial fans with severe instability regions should not be operated at blades angles, rotational speeds, mass flow rates, and pressures that expose the fan to stall conditions.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Surging should not be confused with stalling.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Stalling occurs only if there is insufficient air entering into the fan blades causing separation of flow on the blade surface.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] This situation occurs when the system resistance curve and static pressure curve of the fan intersect have similar slope or parallel to each other.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Rather than intersecting at a definite point the curves intersect over certain region reporting system surge.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] These characteristics are not observed in axial fans.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] This unstable operation results from the development of pressure gradients in the opposite direction of the flow.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Maximum pressure is observed at the discharge of the impeller blade and minimum pressure on the side opposite to the discharge side.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] When the impeller blades are not rotating these adverse pressure gradients pump the flow in the direction opposite to the direction of the fan.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The result is the oscillation of the fan blades creating vibrations and hence noise.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] This effect is seen only in case of multiple fans.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] The air flow capacities of the fans are compared and connected in same outlet or same inlet conditions.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] This causes noise, specifically referred to as Beating in case of fans in parallel.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] To avoid beating use is made of differing inlet conditions, differences in rotational speeds of the fans, etc.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] By designing the fan blades with proper hub-to-tip ratio and analyzing performance on the number of blades so that the flow doesn't separate on the blade surface these effects can be reduced.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Some of the methods to overcome these effects are re-circulation of excess air through the fan, axial fans are high specific speed devices operating them at high efficiency and to minimize the effects they have to be operated at low speeds.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] For controlling and directing the flow use of guide vanes is suggested.
[src:impeller/axial-fan-design] Turbulent flows at the inlet and outlet of the fans cause stalling so the flow should be made laminar by the introduction of a stator to prevent the effect.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] An **axial-flow pump**, or **AFP**, is a common type of pump that essentially consists of a propeller (an axial impeller) in a pipe.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] The propeller can be driven directly by a sealed motor in the pipe or by electric motor or petrol/diesel engines mounted to the pipe from the outside or by a right-angle drive shaft that pierces the pipe.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] Fluid particles, in course of their flow through the pump, do not change their radial locations since the change in radius at the entry (called 'suction') and the exit (called 'discharge') of the pump is very small.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] An axial flow pump has a propeller-type of impeller running in a casing.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] The pressure in an axial flow pump is developed by the flow of liquid over the blades of impeller.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] The fluid is pushed in a direction parallel to the shaft of the impeller, that is, fluid particles, in course of their flow through the pump, do not change their radial locations.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] It allows the fluid to enter the impeller axially and discharge the fluid nearly axially.
[src:impeller/axial-flow-pump] The propeller of an axial flow pump is driven by a motor.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] An **impeller**, or **impellor**, is a driven rotor used to increase the pressure and flow of a fluid.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] It is the opposite of a turbine, which extracts energy from, and reduces the pressure of, a flowing fluid.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Strictly speaking, propellers are a sub-class of impellers where the flow both enters and leaves axially, but in many contexts the term "impeller" is reserved for *non*-propeller rotors where the flow enters axially and leaves radially, especially when creating suction in a pump or compressor.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] An impeller is a rotating component of a centrifugal pump that accelerates fluid outward from the center of rotation, thus transferring energy from the motor that drives the pump to the fluid being pumped.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The acceleration generates output pressure when the outward movement of the fluid is confined by the pump casing.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] An impeller is usually a short cylinder with an open inlet (called an eye) to accept incoming fluid, vanes to push the fluid radially, and a splined, keyed, or threaded bore to accept a drive shaft.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] It can be cheaper to cast an impeller and its spindle as one piece, rather than separately.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] An open impeller has a hub with attached vanes and is mounted on a shaft.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The vanes do not have a wall, making open impellers slightly weaker than closed or semi-closed impellers.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] However, as the side plate is not fixed to the inlet side of the vane, the blade stresses are significantly lower.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] In pumps, the fluid enters the impeller's eye, where vanes add energy and direct it to the nozzle discharge.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] A close clearance between vanes and pump volute or back plate prevent most of fluid from flowing back.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Wear on the bowl and edge of vane can be compensated by adjusting the clearance to maintain efficiency over time.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Because the internal parts are visible, open impellers are easier to inspect for damage and maintain than closed impellers.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] They can also be more easily modified to change flow properties.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Open impellers operate on a narrow range of specific speed.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Open impellers are usually faster and easier to maintain.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] For small pumps and those dealing with suspended solids, open impellers are generally used.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Sand locking does not occur as easily as with closed type.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] A semi-closed impeller has an additional back wall, giving it more strength.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] These impellers can pass mixed solid-liquid mixtures at the cost of reduced efficiency.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The construction of closed impellers includes additional back and front walls on both sides of vanes that enhances its strength.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] This also reduces the thrust load on the shaft, increasing bearing life and reliability and reducing shafting cost.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] However, this more complicated design, including the use of additional wear rings, makes closed impellers more difficult to manufacture and more expensive than open impellers.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] A closed impeller's efficiency decreases as wear ring clearance increases with use.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] However, adjustment of impeller bowl clearance does not affect the wear on vanes as critically as open impeller.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Closed impellers can be used on a wider range specific speed than open impellers.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] They are generally used in large pumps and clear water applications.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] These impellers can't perform effectively with solids and become difficult to clean if clogged.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The screw impeller design aligns more with an axial progressive channel that allows for solids to be openly handled when rotating.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The main part of a centrifugal compressor is the impeller.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] An open impeller has no cover, therefore it can work at higher speeds.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] A compressor with a covered impeller can have more stages than one that has an open impeller.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Some impellers are similar to small propellers but without the large blades.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Among other uses, they are used in water jets to power high speed boats.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Because impellers do not have large blades to turn, they can spin at much higher speeds than propellers.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The water forced through the impeller is channeled by the housing, creating a water jet that propels the vessel forward.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The housing is normally tapered into a nozzle to increase the speed of the water, which also creates a Venturi effect in which low pressure behind the impeller pulls more water towards the blades, tending to increase the speed.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] To work efficiently, there must be a close fit between the impeller and the housing.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The housing is normally fitted with a replaceable *wear ring* which tends to wear as sand or other particles are thrown against the housing side by the impeller.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Vessels using impellers are normally steered by changing the direction of the water jet.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Compare to propeller and jet aircraft engines.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Impellers in agitated tanks are used to mix fluids or slurry in the tank.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] This can be used to combine materials in the form of solids, liquids and gas.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Mixing the fluids in a tank is very important if there are gradients in conditions such as temperature or concentration.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Radial flow impellers impose essentially shear stress to the fluid, and are used, for example, to mix immiscible liquids or in general when there is a deformable interface to break.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Another application of radial flow impellers is the mixing of very viscous fluids.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Axial flow impellers impose essentially bulk motion and are used on homogenization processes, in which increased fluid volumetric flow rate is important.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Propellers are axial thrust-giving elements.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] These elements give a very high degree of swirling in the vessel.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] The flow pattern generated in the fluid resembles a helix.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Some constructions of top loading washing machines use impellers to agitate the laundry during washing.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Fire services in the United Kingdom and many countries of the Commonwealth use a stylized depiction of an impeller as a rank badge.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Officers wear one or more on their epaulettes or the collar of their firefighting uniform as an equivalent to the "pips" worn by the army and police.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Air pumps, such as the roots blower, use meshing impellers to move air through a system.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Applications include blast furnaces, ventilation systems, and superchargers for internal combustion engines.
[src:impeller/bladelet-impeller] Impellers are an integral part of axial-flow pumps, used in ventricular assist devices to augment or fully replace cardiac function.
[src:impeller/casting] Throughout history, metal casting has been used to make tools, weapons, and religious objects.
[src:impeller/casting] Metal casting history and development can be traced back to Southern Asia (China, India, etc).
[src:impeller/casting] Southern Asian traditions and religions relied heavily on statue and relic castings.
[src:impeller/casting] These items were frequently made from a copper alloy laced with lead.
[src:impeller/casting] Since the beginning of metallurgy the majority of castings were simple one- to two-piece molds fashioned from either stone or ceramics.
[src:impeller/casting] However, there is evidence of lost wax castings in numerous ancient civilizations.
[src:impeller/casting] The lost wax process originated in ancient Mesopotamia (modern-day Iraq).
[src:impeller/casting] The earliest known record of lost-wax casting is a clay tablet written in cuneiform in the ancient city of Sparta, Babylon (modern-day Iraq), which specifically records how much wax is needed to cast a key.
[src:impeller/casting] The earliest-known castings in the global archaeological record were made in open stone molds.
[src:impeller/casting] There are two types of lost wax methods: direct lost wax method and indirect lost wax method.
[src:impeller/casting] The direct molding method is to make the wax material into the same wax mold as the casting by hand or other tools; the indirect molding method is to make the wax mold through the mold.
[src:impeller/casting] The direct molding method requires craftsmen to have a high technical level; otherwise, the quality of castings cannot be guaranteed.
[src:impeller/casting] However, the limitation of manual direct molding is that its efficiency is too low to achieve mass production.
[src:impeller/casting] In this regard, indirect moulding has advantages.
[src:impeller/casting] In indirect moulding, artisans usually make moulds from stone, wood, clay or other plastic materials.
[src:impeller/casting] Early civilizations discovered lead aided in the fluidity of molten copper, allowing them to cast more intricate designs.
[src:impeller/casting] For example, the dancing girl of Mohenjo-daro is a copper alloy casting that most likely utilizes the lost wax technique.
[src:impeller/casting] Lost wax casting can be dated back to 4000 BC or the Chalcolithic period.
[src:impeller/casting] One of the oldest studied examples of this technique is a 6,000-year-old amulet from the Indus Valley Civilisation.
[src:impeller/casting] India is attributed as one of the first civilizations to use casting methods to mass-produce coins.
[src:impeller/casting] Around the middle of the first millennium BC (1000 BC – 1 BC), coins used were made from silver, but as the millennium progressed, the coins shifted to a cast copper alloy.
[src:impeller/casting] New technology was developed to mass-produce the new copper coins.
[src:impeller/casting] Introduced was a multi-piece, stackable coin template mold.
[src:impeller/casting] Multiple molds were placed on top of one another into a clay cylinder so molten metal could be poured down the center, filling and solidifying in the open spaces.
[src:impeller/casting] This process allowed one hundred coins to be produced simultaneously.
[src:impeller/casting] In the Middle East and West Africa, the lost wax technique was used very early in their metallurgy traditions, while China adopted it much later.
[src:impeller/casting] In Western Europe lost wax techniques are considered to have been hardly used especially in comparison to that of the Indus Valley Civilisation.
[src:impeller/casting] There were no pieces of lost wax found in the capital of Anyang during the Shang dynasty (1600–1040 BC) while a large amount (100,000 pieces) of piece-mould fragments were found.
[src:impeller/casting] This led to the conclusion that lost wax was not performed in the capital during this dynasty.
[src:impeller/casting] However, the discovery of a mask made using the investment moulding dated at around 1300 BC indicated that the lost wax technique may have influenced other regions in China.
[src:impeller/casting] Historians debate the origin of the development of the cannon, but most evidence points to Turkey and Central Asia in the 18th and 19th century.
[src:impeller/casting] The casting process of a cannon is a bit more complex with the use of a clay core, a template which has clay moulded around it and then broken out, followed by an assembly in a casting pit that involves binding the casting with iron bands.
[src:impeller/casting] In metalworking, metal is heated until it becomes liquid and is then poured into a mold.
[src:impeller/casting] The mold is a hollow cavity that includes the desired shape, but the mold also includes runners and risers that enable the metal to fill the mold.
[src:impeller/casting] The mold and the metal are then cooled until the metal solidifies.
[src:impeller/casting] The solidified part (the casting) is then recovered from the mold.
[src:impeller/casting] Subsequent operations remove excess material caused by the casting process (such as the runners and risers).
[src:impeller/casting] Plaster and other chemical curing materials, such as concrete and plastic resin, may be cast using single-use *waste* molds as noted above, multiple-use 'piece' molds, or molds made of small rigid pieces or of flexible material such as latex rubber (which is in turn supported by an exterior mold).
[src:impeller/casting] When casting plaster or concrete, the material surface is flat and lacks transparency.
[src:impeller/casting] Often topical treatments are applied to the surface.
[src:impeller/casting] For example, painting and etching can be used in a way that gives the appearance of metal or stone.
[src:impeller/casting] Alternatively, the material is altered in its initial casting process and may contain colored sand so as to give an appearance of stone.
[src:impeller/casting] By casting concrete, rather than plaster, it is possible to create sculptures, fountains, or seating for outdoor use.
[src:impeller/casting] A simulation of high-quality marble may be made using certain chemically-set plastic resins (for example, epoxy or polyester, which are thermosetting polymers) with powdered stone added for coloration, often with multiple colors worked in.
[src:impeller/casting] The latter is a common means of making washstands, washstand tops and shower stalls, with the skilled working of multiple colors resulting in simulated staining patterns as is often found in natural marble or travertine.
[src:impeller/casting] Raw castings often contain irregularities caused by seams and imperfections in the molds, as well as access ports for pouring material into the molds.
[src:impeller/casting] The process of cutting, grinding, shaving or sanding away these unwanted bits is called "fettling" in British English.
[src:impeller/casting] In modern times robotic processes have been developed to perform some of the more repetitive parts of the fettling process, but historically fettlers carried out this arduous work manually, and often in conditions dangerous to their health.
[src:impeller/casting] Fettling can add significantly to the cost of the resulting product, and designers of molds seek to minimize it through the shape of the mold, the material being cast, and sometimes by including decorative elements.
[src:impeller/casting] Casting process simulation uses numerical methods to calculate cast component quality considering mold filling, solidification and cooling, and provides a quantitative prediction of casting mechanical properties, thermal stresses and distortion.
[src:impeller/casting] Simulation accurately describes a cast component's quality up-front before production starts.
[src:impeller/casting] The casting rigging can be designed with respect to the required component properties.
[src:impeller/casting] This has benefits beyond a reduction in pre-production sampling, as the precise layout of the complete casting system also leads to energy, material, and tooling savings.
[src:impeller/casting] The software supports the user in component design, the determination of melting practice and casting methoding through to pattern and mold making, heat treatment, and finishing.
[src:impeller/casting] This saves costs along the entire casting manufacturing route.
[src:impeller/casting] Casting process simulation was initially developed at universities starting from the early '70s, mainly in Europe and in the U.S., and is regarded as the most important innovation in casting technology over the last 50 years.
[src:impeller/casting] Since the late '80s, commercial programs (such as PoligonSoft, AutoCAST and Magma) are available which make it possible for foundries to gain new insight into what is happening inside the mold or die during the casting process.
